## Question

Since mbed OS 5, Communication speed is very slow due to lock / unlock in 1 byte unit.
For example SPI driver:
Because of `lock()` and `unlock()` which are called in the following two functions, 
`lock()` and `unlock()` with mutex function are executed twice every 1 byte transfer. 

<SPI.cpp>
```
void SPI::aquire() {
    lock();
     if (_owner != this) {
        spi_format(&_spi, _bits, _mode, 0);
        spi_frequency(&_spi, _hz);
        _owner = this;
    }
    unlock();
}
```
```
int SPI::write(int value) {
    lock();
    aquire();
    int ret = spi_master_write(&_spi, value);
    unlock();
    return ret;
}
```
When accessing SD by using SPI driver, the communication speed is very slow compared with mbed classic speed. Because it takes time for SD access, music transfer and image transfer may fail.
In mbed classic, communication speed is fast because of `lock()` / `unlock()` with empty function.

In SPI communication, I guess that communication of only 1 byte is rare.
Therefore, it's necessary to lock at application layer so that it will not be interrupted in the middle of communication.
In this case, it's not necessary to lock / unlock in 1 byte unit.
The following `sd-driver` lock the part that not be interrupted in the middle of communication at application layer.
https://github.com/ARMmbed/sd-driver

```
int SDBlockDevice::_cmd(int cmd, int arg) {
    _spi.lock();
    _cs = 0;

    // send a command
    _spi.write(0x40 | cmd);
    _spi.write(arg >> 24);
    _spi.write(arg >> 16);
    _spi.write(arg >> 8);
    _spi.write(arg >> 0);
    _spi.write(0x95);

    // wait for the repsonse (response[7] == 0)
    for (int i = 0; i < SD_COMMAND_TIMEOUT; i++) {
        int response = _spi.write(0xFF);
        if (!(response & 0x80)) {
            _cs = 1;
            _spi.write(0xFF);
            _spi.unlock();
            return response;
        }
    }

    _cs = 1;
    _spi.write(0xFF);
    _spi.unlock();
    return -1; // timeout
}
```
